he overall chemical composition of a rock rather than which mineral are present the majority of sio in igneous rocks is not present as quartz sio silicasilicon dioxide but is contained within other silicates minerals such as olive and feldspar its is easier to link sio percentage to the colour as a short cut for identification the mafic rocks are rich in dark coloured ferromagnesian minerals such as olivine and augite silicic rocks are rich in light coloured minerals such as quartz and feldspar but colour can be misleading as in rock such as obsidian which is dark coloured however is silicicfelsic minerals silicicthe felsic minerals are quartz and feldspar which are bother rich in silicaquartz silicic only found in silicic or intermediate rocks  the magma must be over saturated with silica so that there is excess silica after the rock forming minerals have crystallised to form quartz vitreous lutre  glassy white grey to transparent  no cleavage  made entirely of silicafeldsparssilicic most common rock forming mineral in igneous rocks  potassium feldsparorthoclase is only found in silicic and intermediate rocks so good mineral to use as classification often found as large phenocrysts and groundmass in granite  pink colour of k feldspar make its easy to identify  grey or white feldspar is plagioclase  hand lens glassy apprentice and smooth crystals cleavage  hardness   cleavage in two directions  vitreousmafic minerals these are the minerals that contain both magnesium and iron and are referred to as ferromagnesian they are dark coloured and silica poorbiotite and muscovite mica mafic the micas are biotite found in silica to intermediate rocks and muscovite found in silicic rocks only shiny black crystals of biotite can easily be identified through the silvery flakes of muscovite micas can be starched with copper coin and are the only igneous rocks soft enough fro this test hardness   biotite is black  muscovite is silver  vitreous lustre glassy one perfect cleavage p