ed crystal will have been formed very slowly at deep depths below the surface know as plutonichowever an intrusion that cooled km below the surface will have medium grained crystals but will also have fine grained crystals at the edge were the chilled margin cooled quickly a lava flow that cooled at the surface will have fine grained crystals but if it is very thick then the middle of the flow may have medium grained crystalsvesicular vesicular textures are where gas bubbles are trapped in the lava as it cools rapidly leaving holes where the gas was  the holes are called vesicles are usually oval in shape and are also elongated parallel in the direction of flow  the gas rises so most vesicles are found at the top of a lava flow or sometimes at the edge of an intrusion is commonly found in basalt and pumiceamygdaloidal the amygdaloidal texture is formed when the holes are later infilled by minerals deposited by the ground water is porous which allows water to flow through it  the ground water contains calcium carbonate so calcite will be precipitated in the holes this can happen over millions of years after the minerals was formed is mainly either calcite or quartz however others may also be found each infilled hole is called an amygdale both are around mm however can be largerflow bandingflow banding occurs where layers of darkmafic biotite and light silicic quartz minerals form due to the separation of minerals within in silicic lava flows they will be aligned parallel to the flow direction though they may often be contortedtwisted out of normal shapebecause the lava flow was vicious so flowed slowly often found in rhyoliteporphyritic textures a porphyritic texture forms when there is two stages of cooling to a rocks formation resulting in two different crystal sizes  the large crystals are called phenocrysts and form first by cooling slowly they are surrounded by a finer groundmass which cooled quickly the texture can be found in any igneous rock but is most common in porphyritic basalt and porphyritic granite even though they cooled at different depths  in porphyritic basalt the phenocrysts often plagioclase feldspar start to form slowly in the magma chamber below the volcano when the eruption occurs magma and plagioclase crystals are erupted to the surface where rapid cooling occurs and forms the fine grained crystals of the ground mass  the phenocrysts in a porphyritic granite often potassium feldspar start to form at very slowly at great depths perhaps  km the magma and feldspar crystals move up within the crusts to form a batholith the rest of the magma then cools very slowly to form the coarse grained crystals of the groundmasspoikilitictexture which has small randomly orientated crystals which are enclosed by larger crystalsgranite  silica  silicic  light colour  major intrusion plutonic  coarse grained  mm main minerals quartz k feldspar and biotite and plagioclase feldspar nagranodiorite  silica to  intermediate boundary  major intrusion plutonic  coarse grained mm light colour  main minerals k feldspar plagioclase feldspar biotite and hornblenderhyolite  silica  silicic  flow banding found  volcanic extrusive  fine grained mm light in colour  main minerals quartz k feldspar and biotite and plagioclase feldspar napumice  silica  silicic  volcanic extrusive  fine grained mm light in colour  main minerals quartz k feldspar and biotite and plagioclase feldspar naobsidian  silica  silicic  volcanic extrusive  glassy light in colour  main minerals quartz k feldspar and biotite and plagioclase feldspar nadiorite  silica  intermediate  major intrusion plutonic  coarse grained mm  light in colour  main minerals are potassium feldspar plagioclase feldspar biotite and hornblendeandesite  silica  intermediate  volcanic extrusive fine grained mm light in colour  main minerals are potassium feldspar plagioclase feldspar biotite and hornblendegabbro  silica  mafic  major intrusion plutonic  coarse grained mm  darker in colour  ma